<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1 class="title">☁️ Cloud Fun Facts</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Discover amazing facts about cloud computing!</p>

        <div class="fact-box">
            <p class="fact-text" id="factText">Click the button below to get a fun cloud fact!</p>
        </div>

        <button class="generate-btn" id="generateBtn" onclick="getFact()">
            Generate Fun Fact
        </button>

        <div class="tech-info">
            Powered by AWS Lambda + API Gateway + DynamoDB + Bedrock AI
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // 👇 REPLACE THIS WITH YOUR ACTUAL API ENDPOINT
        const API_URL = 'https://YOUR-API-ID.execute-api.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/funfact';

        async function getFact() {
            const btn = document.getElementById('generateBtn');
            const factText = document.getElementById('factText');
            
            // Show loading
            btn.disabled = true;
            btn.textContent = 'Loading...';
            factText.textContent = 'Getting your fact...';
            factText.className = 'fact-text loading';
            
            try {
                // Call your API
                const response = await fetch(API_URL);
                const data = await response.json();
                
                // Show the fact
                factText.textContent = data.fact;
                factText.className = 'fact-text';
                
            } catch (error) {
                // Show error
                factText.innerHTML = '<div class="error">Could not fetch fact. Check your API endpoint!</div>';
                console.error('Error:', error);
            }
            
            // Reset button
            btn.disabled = false;
            btn.textContent = 'Generate Another Fact';
        }

        // Check if API is configured
        window.onload = function() {
            if (API_URL.includes('YOUR-API-ID')) {
                document.getElementById('factText').innerHTML = 
                    '<div class="error">Please update API_URL in the script with your actual API Gateway endpoint</div>';
            }
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>
👉 What this code does:

Creates a beautiful, responsive web interface
Calls your API Gateway endpoint when button is clicked
Displays cloud fun facts with loading states and error handling
Works on desktop and mobile devices


Step 2: Configure Your API Endpoint
Get your API Gateway URL from Stage 2/3:
Go to API Gateway Console
Select your FunfactsAPI
Go to Stages → default
Copy the Invoke URL
Update the API_URL in your code:
// Replace this line in the HTML file
const API_URL = '<https://abc123def.execute-api.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/funfact>';
👉 Important: Make sure the URL ends with /funfact and includes https://


Step 3: Enable CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)
Since your frontend will be hosted on a different domain than your API, you need to enable CORS:

Go to API Gateway Console → select your HTTP API.
In the left menu, click CORS.


Configure the CORS settings:
Allowed origins → your Amplify frontend domain (or for testing).
Allowed headers → Content-Type,Authorization,X-Amz-Date,X-Api-Key,X-Amz-Security-Token.
Allowed methods → GET,OPTIONS (add POST,PUT,DELETE if needed later).
Expose headers → leave empty unless your frontend needs specific headers.
Max age → e.g. 3600 (seconds) so the browser caches preflight responses.
Click Save.


👉 What's CORS?

CORS allows your web page (hosted on Amplify) to make API calls to your API Gateway
Without CORS, browsers block cross-origin requests for security


Step 4: Deploy Frontend to AWS Amplify
AWS Amplify is perfect for hosting static websites with automatic HTTPS and global CDN.

Create Amplify App:

Go to AWS Amplify Console
Click "Host your web app"
Select "Deploy without Git provider"


Configure app:
App name: cloud-fun-facts-generator
Environment name: production
Method: Drag and drop
Upload Your Code:

Create a ZIP file containing your index.html
Drag the ZIP file to the upload area
Click "Save and deploy"


Wait for deployment (usually takes 1-2 minutes)


Step 5: Test Your Full-Stack Application
Get your Amplify URL:After deployment, you'll get a URL like: https://main.d1234abcd.amplifyapp.com
Test the complete flow:Open your Amplify URL in browser


Click "Generate Fun Fact" button
Should see a cloud fact from your API (via Lambda → DynamoDB → Bedrock)
